data.name: label7.Text
data.value: Vigenère cipher essentially uses a 'key' to function. The 'key' in question is actually a keyword, such as 'cat', 'kshm' or any other such combination of letters. The cipher uses a constantly changing version of the Caesar shift to encode its letters using a tabula rectus- in this way, it is similiar to the Trithemius cipher.

data.name: label4.Text
data.value: The Caesar shift is extremely easy to use. The cipher works by shifting individual letters of a message a set number of places forward. For example, a shift of twenty-two would change 'a' to 'w, 'b' to 'x', and so on. Since there are twenty-six letters in the English alphabet, there are twenty-five possible shifts (the last one being the original letter).
